      "fields": {
        "introSummary": "",
        "body": "<p>\n    CHARLOTTE, N.C. (Oct. 26, 2015) â <a href=\"http://www.perahealth.com/\">PeraHealth</a>, a provider of real-time clinical surveillance software alerting doctors and nurses earlier to serious health problems, has named Ashley Wilkens, R.N., director of pediatric and clinical services.\n</p>\n<p>\n    Wilkens will leverage a decade of clinical informatics experience, including eight years as a practicing pediatric and neonatal nurse, to help PeraHealthâs partner hospitals provide safer, more integrated care. Certified in Lean Six Sigma, Wilkens has implemented strategies that enhanced clinician adoption of advanced technologies and improved patient safety and satisfaction in various healthcare settings â from ambulatory and small community hospitals to large integrated delivery systems. She previously served as a consultant at several electronic health record (EHR) companies.\n</p>\n<p>\n    âAshleyâs unique understanding of the role clinical data plays in improving pediatric care delivery will significantly benefit our childrenâs hospital clients in their efforts to enhance quality and efficiency,â said PeraHealth CEO Stephanie Alexander.\n</p>\n<p>\n    PeraHealth solutions provide childrenâs hospitals with a full picture of a childâs condition, both in the moment and trended over time. Powered by the pediatric Rothman Index (pRI), a disease-agnostic universal patient score for predicting mortality and readmission risk, PeraHealth software automatically pulls data from all major EHR systems. The data is translated into a pRI score and presented in color-coded graphs, allowing care teams to quickly visualize patient condition and take immediate action.\n</p>\n<p>\n    Recent Childrenâs Hospital of Pittsburgh of UPMC <a href=\"http://www.perahealth.com/discover/news/peer-review-childrens-hospital-of-pittsburgh-of-upmcs-electronic-surveillance-framework-could-significantly-reduce-false-positive-diagnoses/\">peer-reviewed research</a> found the pRI can significantly reduce false-positive identification of serious health conditions. According to the research, the pRI had a false-positive rate of just 1 percent, compared to 46 percent for monitoring vital signs, a common indicator of patient condition.\n</p>\n<p>\n    The pRI is currently used by some of the nationâs leading childrenâs hospitals â representing approximately 2,000 beds, 100,000 annual inpatient admissions and 2.6 million annual outpatient visits.\n</p>\n<p>\n    Nationally, clinicians use PeraHealth solutions to:\n</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>Remotely monitor patients across care settings and preempt rapid response team intervention\n    </li>\n    <li>Help determine when to discharge patients\n    </li>\n    <li>Prioritize patient bedside visits and nursing assignments\n    </li>\n    <li>Improve documentation accuracy and timeliness\n    </li>\n    <li>Optimize ICU bed use\n    </li>\n    <li>Recognize and communicate palliative care need\n    </li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n    <strong>About PeraHealth</strong> <strong><br></strong>PeraHealth is transforming healthcare through the intelligent use of data. By leveraging the Rothman Index, a validated patient acuity score, PeraHealth software solutions enable healthcare providers to identify at-risk patients sooner for earlier intervention. Leading hospitals and health systems utilize PeraHealthâs real-time, predictive analytics to improve quality and reduce costs. Clinical results include lowering mortality rates by as much as 30%. For more information, visit PeraHealth.com and @PeraHealth.\n</p>",
        "releaseDate": "2015-10-26",
        "pDFPressRelease": null,
        "mediaContact": "",
        "title": "PeraHealth Bolsters Pediatric Expertise with Addition of Ashley Wilkens, R.N.",
        "slug": "perahealth-bolsters-pediatric-expertise-with-addition-of-ashley-wilkens-r-n"
      }
